Yes. For Xe-LP / UHD 770, the right plan is:

offline-create one tiny VS and one tiny PS
embed them as blobs
build the minimum render batch around them
do not build a general shader system yet

That fits the hardware model: Xe-LP runs programmable work on EUs, and the Render engine consumes command streams through the Render Command Streamer with contexts, ring/batch buffers, and engine state programmed from commands.

The practical sequence
1) Freeze the goal

Make the first pipeline as small as possible:

Vertex shader
input: vec3 position
output: gl_Position = vec4(position, 1.0)
Pixel shader
output: constant color, for example solid green

No textures, no descriptors beyond the render target, no depth, no blending, no instancing, no indexing.

That keeps shader register pressure and state small, which matters on Xe-LP EUs.

2) Decide what your “offline artifact” is

You want to generate and save:

compiled kernel code for VS
compiled kernel code for PS
enough metadata to fill the relevant 3D state packets:
dispatch / enable bits
sampler count = 0
binding table expectations
push constant usage = 0 for bring-up
URB / varying usage

For bring-up, treat this exactly like firmware.

3) Do not invent a compiler first

Use an existing Intel shader compiler path once, offline, on a build machine.

The most realistic way is to use Mesa’s Intel compiler stack as a host-side build tool, because Mesa already carries Gen12/Xe-LP compiler support and state packing support; its release notes and Intel state handling reference ongoing work around 3DSTATE_VS, 3DSTATE_PS, binding tables, and surface state on gfx12+.

What you want from that host tool is not a full app, just:

feed in tiny shaders
target gfx12 / Xe-LP
emit:
VS binary blob
PS binary blob
metadata blob or generated C header
4) Build a tiny offline compiler utility

Make a host-only tool, something like:

tools/xe_lp_shader_bake

Its inputs:

triangle.vert
triangle.frag

Its outputs:

triangle_vs.bin
triangle_ps.bin
triangle_vs.h
triangle_ps.h
triangle_meta.json or a generated triangle_pipeline.h

The generated header should contain things like:

struct xe_shader_blob {
    const uint32_t *code;
    uint32_t code_size;
    uint32_t ksp_bytes;        // kernel start pointer offset base-relative
    uint32_t grf_start;
    uint32_t dispatch_mode;
    uint32_t sampler_count;
    uint32_t binding_table_size;
    uint32_t uses_push_constants;
};

Even if some fields start as placeholders, this structure forces you to separate:

binary code
state programming metadata
5) Keep the first shaders brutally simple

Use something like:

// triangle.vert
#version 450
layout(location = 0) in vec3 in_pos;
void main() {
    gl_Position = vec4(in_pos, 1.0);
}
// triangle.frag
#version 450
layout(location = 0) out vec4 out_color;
void main() {
    out_color = vec4(0.0, 1.0, 0.0, 1.0);
}

No varyings at first if you can help it. A constant-color PS removes a whole class of interpolation/debug issues.

6) Bake the blobs into the kernel

Turn the outputs into:

static const uint32_t xe_lp_vs_code[] = { ... };
static const uint32_t xe_lp_ps_code[] = { ... };
static const struct xe_shader_blob xe_lp_vs = { ... };
static const struct xe_shader_blob xe_lp_ps = { ... };

Then at runtime:

allocate GPU memory for code/state
copy the code
point the relevant 3D state to those addresses

No runtime compilation.

What the runtime side then has to do
7) Create the minimal memory objects

You need GPU-visible memory for at least:

ring buffer
batch buffer
render target surface
vertex buffer
shader code storage
dynamic/state storage
context image / status page if your submission model uses logical contexts

Intel’s public docs describe Render engine execution through ring/batch buffers and logical contexts, with per-context hardware status page and engine state restored from memory.

8) Set up one render context

For the render engine path, you need:

a render-capable context
page tables / address space valid
ring buffer start/head/tail
batch buffer address reachable in GPU VA space

The public Intel docs describe context submission, ring buffer control, and command buffers as the execution mechanism.

9) Emit the minimum batch preamble

Your first batch should be structured roughly like this:

PIPELINE_SELECT → 3D/render mode
STATE_BASE_ADDRESS
cache/flush sync as required
viewport / scissor / raster state
render target surface state
binding tables / shader constant state
3DSTATE_VS
3DSTATE_PS
vertex fetch state
primitive topology + draw
end / flush

The exact packet names and field values must come from the Xe-LP PRM or Mesa’s gfx12 state packers, but this is the right shape.

A useful DG1/Xe-LP-era workaround note from Intel’s public docs: in shader mode, 3DSTATE_CONSTANT_* must be programmed before BTP_* state in the relevant sequence, and there are also PIPELINE_SELECT-related sequencing/workaround concerns.

That means for your first path, keep it simple:

program constants first, even if zero
then binding table pointers
then shader state
10) Program STATE_BASE_ADDRESS carefully

You need base addresses for at least:

surface-state area
dynamic-state area
instruction/state heaps as applicable in your setup

Mesa’s Intel code and related docs repeatedly refer to binding tables being relative to surface state base address and other state relative to dynamic state base address, which is exactly the model you need to mirror.

For first light:

put all state blocks in one simple state BO
align each section conservatively
record offsets in one central struct
11) Build one render-target surface state

Create one color RT surface state that points at your already-working displayable buffer.

Start with:

single RT
simple format like RGBA8/BGRA8, whichever your display path already uses
no auxiliary compression
no MSAA
linear or whatever your display engine path already proved

If scanout format/tiling is uncertain, prefer the most boring working layout first.

12) Build the pixel shader binding table

For the PS, bind only one thing:

binding-table entry 0 → render target surface state

No textures, no samplers.

Even though the PS only writes color, the Render pipeline still expects the shader state and associated surface/binding setup to be coherent.

13) Program 3DSTATE_VS

Point it to your VS kernel blob and set only what is needed:

kernel start pointer
enable dispatch
minimal scratch / no scratch if possible
expected GRF/start-register settings from compiler output
URB/output settings matching your VS result

The only VS job is to export clip position.

14) Program 3DSTATE_PS

Point it to your PS kernel blob and set:

kernel start pointer
sampler count = 0
minimal dispatch width from compiler output
render target write enable
no kill/discard
no depth/stencil interaction
no push constants initially

One important Intel workaround note: on this Xe-LP-era documentation, some conditions involving “pixel shader does not write to RT” interact badly with occlusion behavior, and Intel’s public workaround docs explicitly say software should do a dummy RT write from the shader rather than relying on that bit in some cases. For bring-up, the safe path is simple: make the PS actually write color to RT0.

15) Program constants before binding tables

Even if your constant lengths are zero, explicitly emit the constant-state packets in the correct place before binding-table pointers. Intel’s public workarounds call out this ordering on DG1/Xe-LP-class hardware.

16) Build vertex fetch state

Use the smallest possible vertex format:

struct Vertex {
    float x, y, z;
};

Then emit:

one vertex buffer
one vertex element at slot 0
stride = 12
format = 3x32-float

Avoid 256-bit formats and fancy packing; Intel’s public workaround notes explicitly mention a hardware bug around some 256-bit vertex element scenarios.

17) Use non-indexed draw first

For the first draw:

primitive topology = triangle list
vertex count = 3
instance count = 1
no index buffer

That removes more packet/state variables.

18) Add the final sync and submit

At the tail of the batch:

flush / post-sync as required for visibility
batch end
submit through your ring/context path
wait on status/fence
inspect RT memory directly before blaming scanout
