Bring-up order I would use
Pass 1: prove command submission

Submit a batch that does almost nothing except:

enter render mode
do a known-safe flush/end

Confirm the render ring and context are alive. Intel’s public docs emphasize that command submission is through ring/batch buffers tied to logical contexts, so proving that path first saves time.

Pass 2: prove RT state

Use the render engine to write a solid color if you have any blit/clear-style render path available with minimal state. If not, proceed directly to PS write.

Pass 3: prove PS-only path

If your setup allows a fullscreen/simple draw, use the constant-color PS and verify RT write.

Pass 4: prove VS+PS triangle

Now feed 3 vertices and issue one triangle draw.

Pass 5: only then add varyings

Once constant color works, move to:

VS passes color
PS reads interpolated color
The biggest mistakes to avoid
1) Trying to support “real shaders” too early

You only need:

one VS blob
one PS blob
one fixed binding layout
2) Mixing up code vs state

On Intel, the shader blob is only part of the story. The batch/state around it matters just as much.

3) Starting with push constants

Avoid them in pass 1. Intel’s public workaround notes even call out hazards around zero-length push constant buffers unless addressed correctly.

4) Starting with textures or samplers

Do not.

5) Starting with indexed draws or depth

Do not.

